<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1894-11-01T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1894-11-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="376" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d376">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Adee</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Dun</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1894-11-01"><hi rend="italic">November 1,
                                1894</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 137.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I inclose herewith for your information
                            and the files of the legation copy of a dispatch of the 30th
                                ultimo,<note n="1" xml:id="d376fn1">See <ref target="#pg_119">page
                                    119</ref>.</note> sent to Mr. Denby, United States minister at
                            Peking, in regard to the arrest of two Japanese spies at Shanghai and
                            their delivery into the custody of the Chinese authorities.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Alvey A. Adee</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>